description.text:

Based on the Marlin firmware, with auto-bed-leveling enabled.
STL files need some sanitizing.

OpenSCADs included ("Cubic-10mm.zip"). It's a bit of a mess, but I hope usable. There is some degree of parameterization, such as changing the printer dimensions etc. If you need assistance building one yourself, feel free to post a comment, I'll guide you through.

description.text:
Four section resistor storage solution for the full E24 series. The E24 series has 24 values each of which exist on 6 powers of 10. So for example: 1e0, 1e1, 1e2, 1e3, 1e4, 1e5, 1e6 or as it is on the labels: 1.0, 10, 100, 1k, 10k, 100k, 1M. That means there are a total of 6*24 = 144 different resistor values. Technically the E24 series is for 5% resistors, but it is easy and cheap to get all of these common values as 1% resistors.

These drawers could also be used for other small components and the labels could be easily made out of card stock instead of being printed. The full set of 4 frames, 24 drawers and 144 labels took a bit over 100 hours of printing time. The drawers are about 1.3 kg, the frames 0.67 kg, and the labels about 75 grams. (All in PLA at 15% infill.)

There is a hole in the back of the frame in the middle of each slot which is reinforced for mounting with standard wood screws. You can see the ones I used in the photos. The back of each drawers has a small indented section to fit over the screw head. Each section in the drawers has a rounded floor so that "scraping" components out is significantly easier.

I designed the whole set in Fusion 360. To make the labels easier to do I connected the various labels in a single group with very thin "bars" so that Fusion would allow them to be counted as a single body (which made patterning the text possible). These "bars" will be ignored by any slicer. If you want to make your own labels, use the following info:
Width: 25.8mm (or go a bit higher if you want a more snug fit)
Height: 18.2mm (and here I would suggest actually going a bit lower)
Thickness: 0.8mm (4 layers @ 0.2mm)
Corner fillets: 1mm (important to make the labels slide into the slots easily)
Number height: 8mm
Number font: Artifakt Element Black (nice because the 4 doesn't have a floating center)
Unit height: 9mm
Unit font: Arial (Bold)
You will then need to add in small bits to hold any floating inner areas (for 0,6,8 and 9)

It is supposed to be hard to get them in though, that's intended to make them sit tight without glue. No support needed. The holder joint can be either screwed using countersunk M2 or glued to the track joiner plate. I glue mine.

    • 1x spring about 14mm length, 7,3 mm width (or whatever fits)
    • 1x Opto endstop with TCST2103 (standard) type light barrier

  • Use a file to form the upper end of the screw into a flat swordlike surface (length about 10 - 12 mm).

  • Remove screw head from the other side and form a tip end with the file.

  • Assembly :
    • Slide the screw into the body (swordalike end first). Add the two nut and the spring.
    • Put the sword end into the slot and move both nuts down the thread.
    • Adjust the moveable length of the screw by turning the nuts.
    • Fix the nuts by turning against each other.
    • Attach everything to the servo by using a standard servo arm. Probably an additional small hole for the fixing screw must be drilled.

v3 - without holes for tools,

title: Kossel Mini carriage for IGUS DryLin TWE-04-12

description.text:
A Kossel Mini carriage adapter suitable for linear bearings from IGUS, type TWE-04-12. The horns have been moved to center position and mountings for GT2 open loop belts have been added. The part is a remix from jcrocholl's original Kossel Mini carriage in OpenScad. I have used IGUS DryLinÂ® carriages due to their low noise and lubricant/maintenance free glide pads. Also they are easier to acquire here in Germany than the ones proposed in the original BOM. Linear rails can be ordered directly at the manufacturers website:
http://www.igus.de/wpck/2201/DryLin_T_Miniaturfuehrung

• Slice model and print three carriage adapters.
  • Use M3 allen head screws to mount adapters on carriages.
  • Insert one end of the corresponding GT2 open loop belt into the outer notch with about 2cm of extra length.
  • Bend over the exceeding belt and insert it into the inner notch.
  • Continue with the other end of the belt accordingly.
  • Use M3 allen head screws to mount spherical bearings.
  • Enjoy a smooth ride ;-)

description.text: I normally use my Dremel to clean up my 3D prints and typically get sprinkled over and over with small PLA flakes. This thing screws onto my work bench to hold the hose of my Kaercher vacuum cleaner (diameter approx. 36 mm) so that it can catch at least a little bit of the grinding dust. I also created some custom nozzles to extend the hose a little bit and make it handier to work with.

Parts needed: 1 x top.stl
1 x base.stl
4 x knob.stl
4 x hex nut M5
4 x hex screw M5 x 30 (you will have to try, depending on your vacuum hose) Push the 4 nuts into the base from the bottom and the 4 screw heads into the knobs. Screw the base to your workbench, put your vacuum hose inside and fix it with the top and the 4 thumbscrews. If you like, print one or all of the nozzles and enjoy grinding ;-)

title: Rigidbot single head cooling fan mount Rev-3

description.text:
This is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1381040 that can be printed only by enabling supports. However once printed, and supports removed, I noticed that I had lost the beauty of smooth surfaces, since an issue of the supports is that you can't have a perfect flat surface near the supports area. For this reason I hate the supports and I use them only when absolutely necessary.

So I decided to redesign and split the object in a way that could be printed almost without supports, and have all the surfaces perfectly flat. The supports are affecting only a couple of parts that are hidden inside. As result, once installed the look quality is excellent.

The object is still the same of Rev-2 but just remixed to be printed almost without supports.
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/k2M3JQEEUZd

PARTS REQUIRED:

  • All .STL printed parts
  • 1 screw M3 x 40 mm
  • 1 screw M3 x 25 mm
  • 3 M3 washers
  • 2 nuts M3

BUILD INSTRUCTIONS:
1) Print all parts. The support are required only for the air conveyor.
2) Install the cooler arm inside the main block. It should have the right tolerance to be locked inside without the need of glue. If it does not fit, use a file or sandpaper until you are able to fit with a medium pressure.
3) Carefully remove the supports from the air conveyor.
4) Refine the holes with a 4.5mm drill, and then use a 6mm drill to clean the big top hole and the one on the side. Note that the large side hole is deep only 4mm, do not go over with the drill.
5) Align the air conveyor with the side of the main block, and put the 40mm screw in the side hole of the block. Then, put a washer and nut inside the air conveyor, and carefully screw it until all become steady.
6) Insert the cooler in the air conveyor. Insert a washer in the M3 x 25mm screw, and insert it in the cooler arm hole. Put another washer and the nut.

title: Cube/Sphere Dissection, Kawai Tsugite Style, Cube Joint, Math Puzzle

description.text:
The cube is forever a source of mathematical inspiration! There are so many ways to dissect it for puzzles, insights, or just fun! The Kawai Tsugite dissection is simple and elegant, providing great opportunities for students to play with powerful math and design ideas. One starts with a cube, slices two opposite corners off, and then splits the middle pieces using sketches along an equilateral triangle. One can keep one half of the pieces or choose to assemble both half-cubes.

This is probably an intermediate design project. The same process can also be applied on a sphere within the cube. The result, however, is not as much appealing because of the spherical symmetries.

0.2mm tolerance [ 02mmtolerance, the amount pushed back for the wedge surfaces] should be fine for most printers. 0.1mm tolerance gives some friction. Please feel free to experiment with different levels of tolerance between the wedges.

References:

  1. https://woodgears.ca/puzzles/3way_joint.html

  2. Bu, L. https://www.maa.org/press/periodicals/convergence/exploring-liu-hui-s-cube-puzzle-from-paper-folding-to-3-d-design

description.text:
Update 11/16/2017: Wow guys, thanks for the love! This Thing quickly became one of the most popular I've put up. I'd love to see some Makes if any of you are printing them! Looking forward to seeing these on your hoodies, especially Tesla hoodies. ;)

This is an accessory that can be threaded onto a hoodie drawstring to prevent the string from being pulled up into the abyss that is the hood.

Installation
Push the plastic-encased end of a drawstring through the top hole and push it all the way in. A tiny screwdriver can be helpful for this. Once the end appears at the other end of the part, it can be pulled the rest of the way with a pliers, needle-nose works best.

Part can be threaded all the way onto the string, or left on the end.

If the part fits loosely or the hole is not big enough, I will be willing to upload a file with a differently sized hole if you can tell me how much bigger or smaller it needs to be, and you ask me nicely :)

Printing
It is best to print this part using ABS or another material with high heat tolerance due to the tendency of hoodies and jackets to get left in cars that may become excessively hot inside, and PLA won't stand up to that environment.. Best results come with a glass bed, as the rough finish caused by buildtak can make your piece look unfinished if you don't finish it yourself.

I found it best to print with supports and without raft. Supports are easily removed with a needle nose pliers and a tiny screwdriver to poke into the hole.

Precautions
Remove the stoppers before washing or drying (or any other environments with high temperatures) to avoid melting the part and posing a fire risk.

description.text:
After trying many extruders i always end up coming back to the Flexistruder for reliability, quick filament change and simple design. Recently i started to get some under extrusion. I noticed that my spring was never really straight and im sure some pressure was being lost, since i seem to have plenty torque on the drive gear, it just wouldn't bite well on certain filaments and would slip.

So, i decided to fix the issue with the spring not being straight with a new lever. I redid the lever to align the spring with the body and keep spring tension straight. I also made it fit locally available springs like Menards (PN#88250). It also compresses the spring more for extra tension. I also added a top to the design, which helps keep the lever/bearing straight against the drive gear with the added tension using M3x25mm screws.

Included is a regular and reversed version.
For further details, setup etc, see the original thing.

Hope this is helpful for some.

The solder buddy is, in essence, a station in which you can hold multiple wires for soldering. It includes a space for an average sized sponge to clean your soldering iron. Nor did I discover the concept, this is simply an alternative to the standard stainless steel wire holders that is cost effective and a great demonstration of the powers of 3D printing. The Mandelbulb is a 3D version of the popular Mandelbrot fractal. This fractal is the result of years of collaboration between fractal imaging enthusiasts at fractalforums.com. Learn more at http://www.skytopia.com/project/fractal/mandelbulb.html The initial data was generated with Mandelbulb3D, available here: http://www.fractalforums.com/mandelbulb-3d/ Model versions available: PNG sequence: 2048x2048x2048 binary (zipped) PNG sequence 512x512x512 8-bit (processed with 3D convolution filters, zipped) RAW 8-bit 512x512x512 (processed with 3D convolution filters, zipped) 131MB uncompressed STL isosurface mesh, 6.5 million polygons (small shells removed, zipped) 320MB uncompressed PLY isosurface mesh, 7 million polygons (zipped) 129MB uncompressed STL isosurface mesh, reduced to 700k polys.

I am uploading this model as part of a demonstration of the power of volumetric representation. Models using voxel-based structure are known for having a large memory footprint and being difficult to process, but in the case of models with a very large amount of surface area such as fractals or the lattice structures often used in 3D printing, the volumetric structure has many advantages over polygon formats like STL. The original voxel dataset is presented here as a sequence of PNG images. I further processed the data to a more manageble size, filtered out noise, then generated a polygon mesh that can be produced with 3D printing. For further explanation, please see my blog post on why this is important, called "Voxels vs. Polygons": http://40westdesigns.com/blog/?p=371 Read more on the subject in my post on Engineering.com here: engineering.com/3DPrinting/3DPrintingArticles/ArticleID/4523/2012-The-Beginning-of-the-End-for-Polygons.aspx

I build a Mendel90 from a kit by nop head. This kit included a spoolholder, but only for a particular type of spool (narrow and large radius) which nobody seems to sell around here. So I designed this universal spool holder.
I couldn't be bothered to get any vitamins, so I made it fully printable, meaning you don't need any extra parts and it'll just snap onto your printer!
In the meantime I've been using it for a couple of months now and it works flawlessly. The spool slides over the holder with very little friction.
I've also made it customizable, so you can make it fit onto your 3D printer.

• Either download the .SCAD file or use Customizer to adjust the measurements for your 3D printer.
  • Then print and snap onto your 3D printer.
    Your plastic will shrink slightly after printing, so make sure to add roughly 1mm to the height of your gantry!
    I've rounded the spoolholder to the minimum expected internal radius of a spool. This should help lower the drag on the spool sufficiently.

description.text:
This is an accessory that can be threaded onto a hoodie drawstring to prevent the string from being pulled up into the abyss that is the hood.

Installation
Push the plastic-encased end of a drawstring through the top hole and push it all the way in. A tiny screwdriver can be helpful for this. Once the end appears at the other end of the part, it can be pulled the rest of the way with a pliers, needle-nose works best.

Part can be threaded all the way onto the string, or left on the end.

If the part fits loosely or the hole is not big enough, I will be willing to upload a file with a differently sized hole if you can tell me how much bigger or smaller it needs to be, and you ask me nicely :)

Printing
It is best to print this part using ABS or another material with high heat tolerance due to the tendency of hoodies and jackets to get left in cars that may become excessively hot inside, and PLA won't stand up to that environment.. Best results come with a glass bed, as the rough finish caused by buildtak can make your piece look unfinished if you don't finish it yourself.

I found it best to print without supports or raft.

Precautions
Remove the stoppers before washing or drying (or any other environments with high temperatures) to avoid melting the part and posing a fire risk.

Many thanks to Ashwinder for modeling the logo I remixed for this Thing!

Tower:

title: Cura Lift Head at Z for PETG Print Gap Plugin

description.text:
Well, they say that PETG likes to "lay down" and not be "smooshed down" like other filaments. After the first layer, you should raise the print head slightly so there's a gap between the nozzle and the printed piece. This plugin will let you do it in cura.

How to use it: Put it in your <cura 3x>/plugins/PostProcessingPlugin/scripts directory. You will need to restart Cura. Go to the Extensions menu, then Post-Processing and Modify G Code. You will be able to select the plugin there.

The height should be set to greater than your first layer height but less than your second.

Code was altered from BQ_PauseAtHeight.py plugin.

Thingiverse requires an STL or design file to submit something, so I uploaded a test shape I use to test new filaments. Enjoy!

Tested on Cura 3.0.3
